   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3180_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>13, Stratford Place, <choice><abbr>W.</abbr>
                        <expan>West</expan></choice></addrLine>
                  <addrLine rend="transform:rotateZ(-40deg)">TELEPHONE 3924 GERRARD</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1914-11-01">Nov 1.</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear friend:</salute>
            </opener>

            <p> A <hi rend="underline">long</hi> time ago I directed an envelope to you, as I wanted
               to say how much I liked your poem on the "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_MenWhoMarchAway">Men Who March Away</ref>". My
                     <choice><abbr>sec.</abbr>
                  <expan>secretary</expan></choice>
               <persName ref="#ps:MrsBlake">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Blake</persName>,
                  (who<del>m</del>
               <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Florence</persName> knows,) also likes it so much –
               &amp; I believe <hi rend="underline">often</hi> thinks of it; for here we see, every
               day, crowds of men preparing to go to the <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3180_2.jpg"/>
               Front, sooner or later.</p>
            <p> I am sure many people must have admired your poem – which struck an original note –.
               and so much of the War verse has been poor, or too vindictive – (such as the <hi
                  rend="underline">infuriated</hi> contribution by that railway porter,
                     <choice><abbr>wh.</abbr>
                  <expan>which</expan></choice> does contain, however, some good lines – &amp; has a
               certain power.) – </p>
            <p>I thought <persName ref="#ps:EdmundGosse"><abbr>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></abbr>
                  Gosse's</persName>
               <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3180_3.jpg"/> "to the Dead" strong &amp; pathetic &amp;
               there have been other rather lighter things that I liked. </p>
            <p> I hope you have, – as much as you could do in these times, – enjoyed this wonderful
               second summer? –</p>
            <p> What a tragedy that was about poor <persName ref="#ps:GeorgeDigby">Major
                  Digby</persName>: I had a very sad note from <persName ref="#ps:BirdieIlchester"
                  >Birdie <choice><abbr>I.</abbr>
                     <expan>Ilchester</expan></choice></persName> but she gave no details as to how
               it all happened.–</p>
            <p> I know so many people in sore trouble now – of course–, &amp; a great <pb n="4"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3180_4.jpg"/> many soldiers who are wounded. Others I know have
               been killed – and so far, we don't seem <hi rend="underline">near</hi> the end of it
               all. Dear old <persName ref="#ps:AnnaHirschmann">Anna</persName> is so good about it
               –; loyal to me &amp; fond of <placeName ref="#pl:England">England</placeName>, though
               she loves the <placeName ref="#pl:Rhine">Rhine</placeName> as all who have lived on
               it do.–</p>
            <p> I wish you would write a <hi rend="underline">strong</hi> protest against the wicked
               proposal to demolish <placeName ref="#pl:ClothFair">Cloth Fair</placeName>? <pb n="5"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3180_5.jpg"/> It is really worse to pull down beautiful &amp;
               interesting old buildings in time of <hi rend="underline">peace</hi>, than to burn
               them in the excitement of war. Surely those <placeName ref="#pl:Smithfield"
                  >Smithfield</placeName> houses should be kept as treasured <hi rend="underline"
                  >relics</hi>, even if they are not supposed to be suitable to live in?–</p>
            <p>It is a relief to read things sometimes unconnected with the war – I have first been
               reading <pb n="6" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3180_6.jpg"/>
               <milestone xml:id="m01" unit="section"/>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m02"/> most of <persName ref="#ps:KatharineParnell"
                     >M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Parnell</persName>'s book–. It is a wonderful
               love-story. – &amp; even though she perhaps ought not to have published it, one can't
               help being touched by it.–</p>
            <p> I am by way of returning to <placeName ref="#pl:ShorehamKent">Shoreham</placeName>
               on <choice><abbr>Wed<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>Wednesday</expan></choice> so perhaps some day you will send me a little
               news of you &amp; <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Florence</persName>
               <hi rend="underline">there</hi>? You must be sure to direct <placeName
                  ref="#pl:ShorehamKent">Shoreham</placeName>
               <hi rend="underline">near</hi>
               <placeName ref="#pl:Sevenoaks"><hi rend="underline">Seven</hi>oaks</placeName>.</p>
            <p> I hope Wessex is well?</p>

            <p corresp="#m01" xml:id="h3180a" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">Milner is a greater
               darling than ever. Of course give my love to <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy"
                        ><choice><abbr>F.</abbr>
                     <expan>Florence</expan></choice></persName></p>
            <closer xml:id="h3180b" corresp="#m02" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">
               <salute>
                  <choice><abbr>yr</abbr>
                     <expan>your</expan></choice>
                  <choice><abbr>affec.</abbr>
                     <expan>affectionately</expan></choice> friend</salute>
               <signed>F.H.</signed>
            </closer>

         </div>
